<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Habitat and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. flavida" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="flavida">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">C. flavida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be endemic to the Natural Sanctuary Cerro El Roble (
<geoCoordinate degrees="33" direction="south" minutes="00" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="-33.0">33Â°00'S</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate degrees="71" direction="west" minutes="01" orientation="longitude" precision="925" value="-71.01667">71Â°01' W</geoCoordinate>
), which is part of the coastal mountain range of central Chile (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Distribution map of Calceolaria flavida (triangles) in Chile. Roman numbers represent administrative regions (IV Coquimbo, V Valparaiso, RM Metropolitan Region, VI O'Higgins, VII Maule). Green polygons represent protected areas (La Campana National Park and Natural Sanctuary Cerro El Roble)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.185.71755.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/611517" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">1</figureCitation>
). It can be found on slopes with N-NW orientation at elevations of 1450-2200 m. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lavandero &amp; Santilli" authorityYear="2021" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Calceolarieae" genus="Calceolaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Calceolaria flavida" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="flavida">
